<Project
  title="Neuroplastic Collective Intelligence"
  description="Ongoing research: can neuroplastic communication mechanisms from computational neuroscience improve emergent coordination and functional specialisation in collective AI systems?"
  eyebrow="Ongoing research"
  year="2026 — present"
  role="Independent research"
  stack={['Python', 'PyTorch', 'PettingZoo', 'NetworkX', 'NumPy']}
  next={{ title: 'Humanitarian Aid Platform', href: '/projects/humanitarian-aid-platform' }}
>
  <p class="lede">
    Biological intelligence does not communicate over fixed wiring. Synapses strengthen with use,
    weaken with neglect, and the network’s topology is itself a product of learning. This project
    asks whether the same principle — plasticity in the connections, not just the nodes — can
    improve how collective AI systems coordinate.
  </p>

  <h2>The hypothesis</h2>
  <p>
    In most multi-agent systems, who talks to whom is decided by the designer and frozen before
    training begins. But my dissertation suggested that communication structure is precisely where
    coordination succeeds or fails. Computational neuroscience offers an alternative: let the
    communication graph adapt by rules inspired by neuroplasticity, so that useful channels
    strengthen and useless ones decay. If the hypothesis holds, coordination and functional
    specialisation should <em>emerge from the topology’s own learning</em> rather than needing to
    be designed in.
  </p>

  <h2>The framework</h2>
  <p>
    I am developing a multi-agent framework in which agents learn cooperative tasks while their
    communication network rewires around them:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Hebbian-inspired plasticity</strong> — connection strengths update locally, driven
      by correlated activity between agents rather than by a global controller.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Adaptive communication graphs</strong> — message passing runs over a weighted graph
      whose edges are themselves learnable, implemented with PyTorch and NetworkX.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Dynamic topology</strong> — the interaction structure can sparsify, cluster and
      reorganise during training, and those trajectories are recorded as data.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Functional specialisation</strong> — measuring whether agents differentiate into
      roles as the network shapes who hears what.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Measuring emergence</h2>
  <p>
    Claims about emergent behaviour are easy to make and hard to substantiate, so evaluation is
    the core of the project. I analyse the systems with graph-theoretic measures of the evolving
    topology and information-theoretic measures of what actually flows across it — asking not
    just whether cooperative benchmarks improve, but whether the communication structure carries
    measurable, non-trivial information about the task.
  </p>

  <div class="pull">
    The goal is not another architecture. It is evidence about a question: does letting
    communication itself learn produce coordination that fixed structures cannot reach?
  </div>

  <h2>Why it matters</h2>
  <p>
    As AI systems become collections of interacting agents rather than single models, the
    machinery of coordination becomes a first-class research problem — and a safety-relevant one.
    Systems whose interaction structure adapts transparently, in ways we can measure and
    interpret, are systems we can deploy with more confidence. This project is my current step
    toward doctoral research in that direction.
  </p>
</Project>
